    <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
    <details class="faq-item">
      <summary>How many days per week should a beginner work out at home?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer"><p>Beginners should aim for 3 workout days per week with at least one rest day between sessions. A Monday, Wednesday, Friday schedule works well because it provides consistent training stimulus while allowing 48 hours of recovery between workouts. This recovery time is essential because muscles grow and strengthen during rest, not during the workout itself. As you build fitness over 4 to 6 weeks, you can gradually add a fourth day or incorporate light activity like walking or yoga on rest days.</p></div>
    </details>
    <details class="faq-item">
      <summary>Can you build muscle with just bodyweight exercises?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer"><p>Yes, you can absolutely build muscle with bodyweight exercises, especially as a beginner. Your own body weight provides sufficient resistance to stimulate muscle growth when you are starting out. Studies published in the Journal of Exercise Science and Fitness have shown that bodyweight training produces comparable strength gains to weight training in untrained individuals over 8-week periods. The key is progressive overload — gradually increasing reps, sets, tempo, or exercise difficulty over time. Once standard push-ups become easy, you can progress to diamond push-ups, decline push-ups, or archer push-ups to continue building strength.</p></div>
    </details>
    <details class="faq-item">
      <summary>How long should a beginner home workout last?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer"><p>A beginner home workout should last between 25 and 40 minutes including warm-up and cool-down. This breaks down to approximately 5 minutes of warm-up, 15 to 25 minutes of exercise, and 5 to 10 minutes of stretching and cool-down. Longer is not necessarily better for beginners — shorter, focused sessions reduce the risk of burnout and excessive soreness. Research shows that even 20-minute sessions of moderate-to-vigorous bodyweight exercise produce significant cardiovascular and strength benefits. Quality of movement and consistency matter far more than workout duration.</p></div>
    </details>
    <details class="faq-item">
      <summary>What should I eat before and after a home workout?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer"><p>Before a home workout, eat a small meal containing carbohydrates and a moderate amount of protein about 60 to 90 minutes beforehand. Good options include a banana with peanut butter, yogurt with fruit, or a slice of whole-grain toast with eggs. After your workout, consume a meal or snack with protein and carbohydrates within 1 to 2 hours to support muscle recovery and replenish glycogen stores. Post-workout options include a protein smoothie, chicken with rice, or Greek yogurt with granola. Hydration is also critical — drink water before, during, and after exercise.</p></div>
    </details>
    <details class="faq-item">
      <summary>Is it normal to be very sore after the first week of working out?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer"><p>Yes, experiencing muscle soreness in the first 1 to 2 weeks of a new workout routine is completely normal. This is called delayed onset muscle soreness (DOMS) and typically peaks 24 to 72 hours after exercise. It occurs because your muscles are adapting to new physical demands and undergoing microscopic repair processes that ultimately make them stronger. The soreness should decrease significantly by weeks 2 to 3 as your body adapts. To manage soreness, stay hydrated, eat adequate protein, do light movement on rest days, and consider gentle stretching. However, if you experience sharp pain, joint pain, or soreness that lasts more than 5 days, consult a healthcare professional.</p></div>
    </details>

